2026-04-16 12:41:32 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module output connector polarity / cable pairing between control module and load module (Control Output Cable + and Control Output Cable − swapped at one end)'] hypothesis_explanation='All internal circuits and components tested good: the battery provides ~12 V at the PSU output; the control‑module input sees the full 12 V with correct polarity; and visual / electrical tests show no faults in the relay, sensor circuit, load‑module diode, lamps, or internal wiring. Yet at the load‑module input the ‘+’ conductor is only ~0.36 V above the negative conductor, and the same ~0.36 V appears at the load‑module diode anode referenced to PSU negative, with essentially 0 V at the lamps. Bypassing the diode does not restore operation. This strongly indicates that the load module is not actually in series with the 12 V path but is sitting near ground potential through some high‑resistance or unintended reference, producing a small stray voltage (~0.36 V) rather than being driven from 12 V.   \n\nGiven that all internal paths have been ruled out by prior failed repair attempts, the only remaining plausible root cause is a wiring / configuration error at the inter‑module connection between the control module and the load module: the Control Output Cable (+) and Control Output Cable (−) are mis‑paired or cross‑connected at one end such that the load module’s ‘+’ input is not on the actual switched 12 V conductor. Instead it is effectively tied to the return or to some floating node, resulting in only a small residual voltage (~0.36 V) at the load input and preventing any current through the lamps even when the relay is closed and the diode is bypassed. Repairing the polarity / pairing at this connector should restore full 12 V to the load module and normal lamp operation.'
