2026-04-16 12:42:04 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module internal output wiring / jack between relay output node and external Control Output Cable (+) terminal', 'load module input connector / jack for Load Input Cable (+)'] hypothesis_explanation='All internal active components (battery, power LED, sensor, relay coil, lamps, series diode) and all previously‑suspected series paths have been verified or replaced with no effect. The power supply delivers a solid 12 V, and 12 V is present on the control module’s internal input node, yet only about 0.36 V appears at the load module input and at the anode of the load‑module diode, even when the relay is confirmed closed. When the diode is bypassed, both lamps remain dark, and the return path is good.\n\nThis pattern means that the main +12 V path is intact up to the relay output node, but there is an open or extremely high‑resistance discontinuity specifically between that relay output node and the external Control Output Cable (+) contact, or alternatively between the mating Load Input Cable (+) contact and the internal load‑module diode anode node. All other series segments in this path (PSU to control input, relay contacts themselves, load internal wiring, return wiring) have either been tested explicitly or previously hypothesized and ruled out.\n\nTherefore the most plausible remaining root cause is a fault at one of the two mechanical terminations of the + conductor at the control module output or the load module input (e.g., cracked solder joint or damaged jack contact), so that the cable sees only a leakage path of a few hundred millivolts and cannot deliver current to the lamps.'
