2026-04-16 12:42:23 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module control‑module ground reference (internal 0 V node) being incorrectly tied to the load‑side + output node instead of the true 0 V line (i.e., swapped internal connections of Control Output Cable (+) and (−) with respect to the module’s own circuitry)'] hypothesis_explanation='All hardware elements tested so far behave correctly: the battery provides 12 V at the PSU output; the control‑module input sees 12 V/0 V correctly; the relay is closed; continuity and series‑resistance faults in the + path, − path, lamps, diode, and cabling have all been ruled out by unsuccessful repair attempts and by measurements. Yet only about 0.36 V appears at the load‑module + input node relative to the power‑supply negative, with ~0 V at the load return. Bypassing the series diode does not restore lamp operation, confirming that essentially no 12 V potential exists across the lamp even when the relay is closed.\n\nThis is consistent with the control module’s internal 0 V reference being mis‑connected: its internal ground (used by the light sensor, comparator, and relay drive circuitry) is effectively tied to the conductor that externally is labelled and used as the + output toward the load, while the conductor labelled as − output is actually at the true 0 V of the power supply. In that situation, the module’s electronics can still function (because they see a correct 12 V between their own + and miswired “ground”), the relay can operate normally, and all earlier component‑level tests pass. But the external load sees its + input clamped near the control module’s internal “ground” potential, which is offset only slightly above the true 0 V by small internal drops (for example through the switched‑cables indicator LED path), yielding the observed ~0.36 V at the load + input while the − line is at 0 V.\n\nThus the underlying fault is an internal misconnection of the control module’s ground reference to the wrong external conductor (the output + instead of output −), effectively swapping the module’s own reference relative to the output pair even though the external polarity labels and cables appear correct. Repairing this internal ground/reference wiring so that the module’s electronics reference the same 0 V conductor that is exported as Control Output Cable (−) will restore a full 12 V across the load and normal lamp operation.'
