2026-04-16 12:43:13 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module internal unintended load / leakage path from Control Output Cable (+) node to Control Output Cable (−) / ground (e.g., wrong-value resistor, unintended semiconductor junction, or design/configuration error that permanently clamps the output node at ~0.36 V)'] hypothesis_explanation='All modules and interconnections have repeatedly tested as having correct polarity, continuity, and supply voltage. The battery and power‑supply outputs are at ~12 V, the control‑module input + and relay common are also at ~12 V, and the relay contacts/wiring to the output node show low resistance. Yet, with the relay closed and even with the load module completely disconnected (no load), the Control Output Cable (+) node sits at ~0.36 V relative to ground and does not change with relay operation or potentiometer settings.\n\nThis behaviour cannot be produced by a fault in the load module or cabling, because the same ~0.36 V is present at the control module’s output + node even when the load is removed. It also cannot be due to a high series resistance from relay common to output + because with the output unloaded, any finite resistance from a 12 V source would make the output node float to ~12 V. Therefore, the only remaining explanation is that the output + node is being clamped toward ground by an unintended internal load/leakage path: a wrong‑value resistor, misconnected component, or other low‑impedance path from the Control Output Cable (+) node to the module’s 0 V node. The observed ~0.36 V is then simply the small voltage the relay/common can drive across this strong shunt to ground, consistent both with and without the load attached.\n\nThus, the root cause is an internal fault in the ambient sensor module consisting of an unintended or incorrect low‑impedance path between the Control Output Cable (+) node and ground, which permanently holds the output at about 0.36 V and prevents the load lamps from lighting even though the relay and supply are otherwise healthy.'
