2026-04-16 12:43:44 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module relay contact configuration / wiring (relay common and normally-closed contact both tied to Control Input Cable (+) instead of common to input+ and NC to output+ , or otherwise miswired so that the output + node is not actually on the relay contact)'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show ~12 V present at the control module input + and at the relay common node, but only ~0.36 V at the Control Output Cable (+) node. With the output unloaded, continuity tests report only about 0.1 Ω between Control Input Cable (+), Control Output Cable (+), and Control Output Cable (−), which contradicts the voltage measurements if the relay contact path were correctly implemented. This combination strongly suggests that the relay’s output contact (or its PCB wiring) is misconfigured: the relay common terminal and the normally-closed terminal (or wiper and one throw) have been wired together to the input + node, while the terminal that should connect to the Control Output Cable (+) is either left floating or incorrectly tied into the network, causing the output node to sit at a small bias (~0.36 V) rather than follow the 12 V at relay common. In other words, the internal wiring of the relay contacts relative to the Control Output Cable (+) is wrong, so that the nominally ‘closed’ relay state does not actually connect the 12 V rail to the output + lead. Repairing/replacing the relay contact wiring so that relay common is on the input + side and the appropriate throw contact is on the Control Output Cable (+) should restore full 12 V to the load module and allow the lamps to operate.'
